  "text": "The SC, especially the SL of the SC, receives direct retinal input and mediates visual threat processing [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . To investigate whether the IL of the SC receiving somatosensory input reflects visual threat signals, we injected AAV9-CaMKIIα-GCaMP6s into the SC and optical fibers were implanted into the IL. Fiber photometry was used to record calcium transients in CaMKIIα-positive neurons in the IL in response to a black looming in the upper visual field (Figure 4A) . A white looming in the upper visual field was used as a control, as it does not trigger flight-to-nest behavior (Figures 4B,C) . The IL of SC CaMKIIα-positive neurons exhibited a significant increase in the activity after presentation of a black LS in the upper visual field (9.52 ± 2.13%, F/F mean) compared with the white LS in the upper visual field (0.98 ± 0.74%, F/F mean). Calcium signal onset to looming overhead stimulus rapidly increased (15% of peak signal as the onset time point) with a latency of 0.71 ± 0.18 s and peak signal of 19.08 ± 3%, F/F (Figures 4D,E) . Taken together, these data demonstrate the IL of SC CaMKIIα-positive neurons encode visual threat processing.",
